snippet.textDisplay:
Absolutely nothing about microservices demands that you run them in a VM or a container. And starting multiple instances of a container on the same machine does not magically grant you more resources. That is, unless the service is badly programmed.
A VM or container is only useful if you want to easily (and usually dynamically) spread your services over multiple machines.

snippet.textDisplay:
Terrible video.
You've made a mess out of deployment strategy; processes in VMs vs. containers. into the whole mess you've added a software architecture decision which is monolithic vs micro-services.
Just to be clean - you can have a microservice or SOA architecture while running processes inside VMs (valid and common strategy).
Kube is one way to do containers in production environments, the are lots of other container orchestrators widely used in production environments.

In addition - the kube nodes probably run on a... VM :D
